<div class="solution" acro="IVLT.T30">
<h5 class="solution">
<span class="type">Solution</span> <span class="acro">IVLT.T30</span> <span class="contributor"><a knowl="./knowls/contributor.robertbeezer.knowl">Robert Beezer</a></span>
</h5>Since $U$ and $V$ are isomorphic, there is at least one isomorphism between them (<a class="knowl" acro="IVS" type="Definition" title="Isomorphic Vector Spaces" knowl="./knowls/definition.IVS.knowl">Definition IVS</a>), say $\ltdefn{T}{U}{V}$.  As such, $T$ is an invertible linear transformation.<br><br>
For $\alpha\in\complexes$ define the linear transformation $\ltdefn{S}{V}{V}$ by $\lt{S}{\vect{v}}=\alpha\vect{v}$.  Convince yourself that when $\alpha\neq 0$, $S$ is an invertible linear transformation (<a class="knowl" acro="IVLT" type="Definition" title="Invertible Linear Transformations" knowl="./knowls/definition.IVLT.knowl">Definition IVLT</a>).  Then the composition, $\ltdefn{\compose{S}{T}}{U}{V}$, is an invertible linear transformation by <a class="knowl" acro="CIVLT" type="Theorem" title="Composition of Invertible Linear Transformations" knowl="./knowls/theorem.CIVLT.knowl">Theorem CIVLT</a>.  Convince yourself that each nonzero value of $\alpha$ gives rise to a different function for $\compose{S}{T}$, which will require the selection of a nonzero vector from $U$.  Then we have constructed infinitely many isomorphisms from $U$ to $V$.
</div>
